    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "### A. Strong Predictors With Clear Separation\n",
        "\n",
        "These variables show meaningful separation between approved and non-approved applicants and are likely to provide strong predictive value in modeling credit approval outcomes.\n",
        "\n",
        "#### 1. Credit Score\n",
        "There is clear separation in median values between approved and non-approved applicants. A substantial proportion of rejected applicants exhibit credit scores near zero (noting the variable appears scaled in this dataset), while approved applicants generally display higher values. This suggests strong discriminatory power and aligns with established credit scoring practices where credit history is a primary determinant of approval.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Recommended Actions:**\n",
        "- Confirm the scaling methodology applied to credit scores.\n",
        "- Retain as a primary predictor in modeling.\n",
        "- Evaluate nonlinear effects or threshold behavior.\n",
        "- Assess interaction with income, debt, and employment variables.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "#### 2. Years Employed\n",
        "Approved applicants tend to have longer employment histories. The interquartile range for rejected applicants is concentrated roughly between 0–1 years, whereas approved applicants extend closer to 0–5 years. This pattern supports the interpretation that employment stability is associated with repayment reliability.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Recommended Actions:**\n",
        "- Consider modeling employment tenure as a continuous predictor.\n",
        "- Evaluate interaction with income and credit score.\n",
        "- Assess whether employment duration captures broader financial stability.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### B. Moderately Informative Predictors Requiring Careful Interpretation\n",
        "\n",
        "These variables show some separation but also exhibit overlap or potential confounding influences.\n",
        "\n",
        "#### 3. Debt\n",
        "While some separation exists between approval groups, there is substantial overlap. Higher debt levels occasionally appear among approved applicants, which may reflect higher income levels, larger credit limits, or longer credit histories rather than debt itself driving approval outcomes.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Recommended Actions:**\n",
        "- Evaluate debt-to-income ratio as a more informative feature.\n",
        "- Investigate correlations with income and credit score.\n",
        "- Avoid interpreting debt in isolation without considering repayment capacity.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "#### 4. Income\n",
        "Income displays noticeable skewness with several extreme outliers. Although approved applicants tend to show somewhat higher income levels, the variability and skewness may obscure its predictive value if used directly.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Recommended Actions:**\n",
        "- Apply log transformation or normalization to reduce skewness.\n",
        "- Investigate outlier handling strategies.\n",
        "- Evaluate interaction with employment stability and credit score.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### C. Weak or Indirect Predictors\n",
        "\n",
        "These variables exhibit limited separation between approval groups and may have weaker independent predictive value.\n",
        "\n",
        "#### 5. Age\n",
