        "**FINAL REGRESSION FINDINGS**:\n",
        "\n",
        "    - All regularized regression models (LASSO, Ridge, Elastic Net) outperformed the baseline logistic regression model. This indicates that regularization improves generalization by reducing overfitting and mitigating the impact of noisy or less informative predictors.\n",
        "    \n",
        "    - Models that perform feature selection (LASSO and Elastic Net) outperformed Ridge regression. This suggests that some predictors contribute limited signal and that fully removing certain variables is more effective than simply shrinking all coefficients.\n",
        "\n",
        "    - LASSO and Elastic Net achieved nearly identical performance. This implies that the optimal Elastic Net solution leaned heavily toward L1 regularization, meaning variable removal played a more important role than coefficient shrinkage in improving predictive performance.\n",
        "\n",
        "*Best Model*: The best-performing model was LASSO Logistic Regression, which achieved the highest overall performance metrics (Test Fβ, ROC-AUC, and Accuracy). Although the difference between LASSO and Elastic Net was minimal, LASSO demonstrated slightly stronger generalization performance.\n",
        "\n",
        "This suggests that enforcing sparsity—completely removing weaker predictors—was more beneficial for this dataset than retaining them with small, shrunk coefficients. Given its strong predictive performance and built-in feature selection capability, LASSO is selected as the preferred regression model.\n",
        "\n",
        "***Future Testing & Interpretation***:\n",
        "\n",
        "Across the majority of regression models, several predictors consistently emerged as influential:\n",
        "\n",
        "    - Prior Default had the largest negative coefficient magnitude across all models, indicating a substantial reduction in the likelihood of approval. This aligns with domain expectations, as past default behavior is a strong indicator of credit risk.\n",
        "\n",
        "    - Certain industries (e.g., Healthcare and Consumer Discretionary) were associated with lower approval likelihood. While the magnitude varied slightly across regularization methods, the direction remained consistent.\n",
        "\n",
        "    - Variables such as High Credit Score, Income (log-transformed), Employment Status, Years Employed, and Bank Customer Status were positively associated with approval likelihood across models, suggesting these characteristics contribute meaningfully to creditworthiness assessments.\n",
        "\n",
        "    - The interaction term Debt × Moderate Credit Score appears to capture nuanced behavior, indicating that debt burden may be interpreted differently depending on the borrower’s credit profile.\n",
        "\n",
        "    - The models also showed that the variable Ethnicity_Latino had a negative coefficient in multiple specifications. However, this finding should not be interpreted causally. We need to explore if theres structural correlations between someones ethnicity and other financial variables in the data, which could find socioeconomic patterns that influence this result. This could be done through exploring correlations between this and financial predictors.\n",
        "\n",
