      "source": [
        "**Findings**:\n",
        "\n",
        "The tuned XGBoost model performed strongly overall but slightly underperformed compared to the tuned Random Forest model, particularly in terms of the Fβ score. While XGBoost maintained high recall and competitive ROC-AUC, Random Forest achieved perfect recall while maintaining similar precision, leading to a higher Fβ score under the recall-weighted evaluation objective.\n",
        "\n",
        "This suggests that while XGBoost effectively captured nonlinear relationships and interactions within the dataset, its more aggressive boosting structure may have introduced slightly less stable probability estimates compared to the ensemble averaging behavior of Random Forest.\n",
        "\n",
        "In this dataset, Random Forest’s variance reduction through bagging appears to align better with the evaluation objective emphasizing recall while maintaining classification reliability."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "filvsLMzWByR"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**Final Comparison Insight**\n",
        "\n",
        "While XGBoost demonstrated strong predictive performance and effective nonlinear modeling, the tuned Random Forest model achieved the highest Fβ score and perfect recall on the test dataset. This suggests that ensemble averaging via bagging produced slightly more stable probability estimates than gradient boosting under the chosen recall-focused evaluation objective.\n",
        "\n",
        "Additionally, the models displayed different regularization preferences: logistic regression benefited from L1 regularization (feature selection), while the nonlinear XGBoost model favored stronger L2 regularization, indicating that shrinkage rather than feature elimination improved stability for boosted tree models."
      ],
