        "## Final Model Findings & Interpretation\n",
        "\n",
        "### Best Predictive Model: Random Forest\n",
        "\n",
        "The tuned Random Forest model demonstrated the strongest overall predictive performance among all models tested. It achieved the highest test Fβ score under the recall-weighted evaluation objective while maintaining strong ROC-AUC, accuracy, and precision metrics. Importantly, the model achieved near-perfect recall, meaning it successfully identified almost all applicants likely to be approved without an excessive increase in false positives.\n",
        "\n",
        "This strong performance likely stems from the model’s ensemble structure:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Averaging hundreds of decision trees reduces variance and stabilizes predictions.\n",
        "- Random feature subsampling allows the model to capture nonlinear relationships and interaction effects without heavy overfitting.\n",
        "- The model is robust to correlated predictors, which are common in financial datasets.\n",
        "\n",
        "Because credit approval decisions often involve complex interactions between income, credit history, employment stability, and demographic factors, the Random Forest model appears best suited for predictive deployment in this context.\n",
        "\n",
        "However, while predictive performance is strong, Random Forest models are less interpretable than regression-based approaches. For this reason, a complementary interpretable model was also selected.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### Most Interpretable Model: LASSO Logistic Regression\n",
        "\n",
        "Among regression models, LASSO logistic regression provided the best balance of interpretability and predictive performance. All regularized regression models (LASSO, Ridge, Elastic Net) outperformed baseline logistic regression, indicating that regularization improves generalization by reducing overfitting and mitigating noise from less informative predictors.\n",
        "\n",
        "Models incorporating feature selection (LASSO and Elastic Net) slightly outperformed Ridge regression, suggesting that removing weak predictors entirely was more effective than simply shrinking all coefficients. Elastic Net converged toward an L1-dominant solution, reinforcing that sparsity was beneficial in this dataset.\n",
        "\n",
        "Because LASSO maintains coefficient interpretability while achieving strong performance, it serves as the primary explanatory model for understanding approval drivers.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### Key Predictors of Credit Approval (Regression Interpretation)\n",
        "\n",
        "Several predictors consistently emerged as influential across regression models:\n",
        "\n",
        "**Strong Negative Predictors**\n",
        "- Prior Default showed the largest negative coefficient magnitude across models, indicating a substantial reduction in approval likelihood. This aligns with expected credit risk behavior.\n",
        "- Some industry categories (notably Healthcare and Consumer Discretionary) were associated with slightly lower approval likelihood, potentially reflecting sector-specific income volatility or employment patterns.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Strong Positive Predictors**\n",
        "- High credit score and higher income (log-transformed) consistently increased approval probability.\n",
        "- Employment status and years employed suggest financial stability is an important approval factor.\n",
        "- Bank customer status positively influenced approval likelihood, possibly reflecting existing financial relationships or additional data availability.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Interaction Effects**\n",
        "- The interaction term Debt × Moderate Credit Score suggests debt burden may be interpreted differently depending on overall credit profile, indicating nuanced lender decision behavior.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Demographic Variables**\n",
        "- The Ethnicity_Latino variable showed a negative coefficient in several models. This should not be interpreted causally. Further analysis is required to assess whether this reflects underlying socioeconomic correlations rather than direct bias.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### Integrated Modeling Insight\n",
        "\n",
        "Together, the modeling results suggest:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Credit approval likelihood is influenced by both linear financial indicators and nonlinear interaction effects.\n",
        "- Regularized regression models capture the primary linear structure effectively.\n",
        "- Ensemble tree models better capture nonlinear interactions and complex segmentation patterns.\n",
        "\n",
        "Therefore, a dual-model strategy is appropriate:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Random Forest as the primary predictive model.\n",
        "- LASSO logistic regression as the primary explanatory model.\n",
