    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**Demographic Disparity Analysis**\n",
        "\n",
        "A descriptive analysis of approval rates shows that Latino applicants in the dataset were approved at a substantially lower rate (14%) compared with other ethnic groups (42–63%). To investigate whether this disparity could be explained by differences in financial characteristics, a comparison of key predictors was conducted.\n",
        "\n",
        "Latino applicants in the dataset exhibited several characteristics associated with higher credit risk, including lower income, fewer years of employment, higher average debt levels, and a substantially higher rate of prior default. These factors are known drivers of approval decisions and likely contribute to the observed disparity in approval outcomes.\n",
        "\n",
        "A logistic regression model was then estimated to control for key financial predictors including debt, income, employment status, credit score category, prior default history, and bank customer status. After controlling for these variables, the Latino ethnicity indicator remained negative and statistically significant (β = −1.385, p = 0.018), corresponding to an odds ratio of approximately 0.25.\n",
        "\n",
        "This result suggests that Latino applicants in the dataset have lower approval odds even after accounting for the observed financial variables. However, this finding should not be interpreted as evidence of causal discrimination. The dataset may omit relevant factors that influence approval decisions, and the Latino subgroup contains a relatively small sample size, which may affect estimate stability. Further analysis with larger datasets and additional financial variables would be required to draw stronger conclusions regarding potential bias."
      ],
